# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1906-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1906-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1906-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1906-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1906-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1906-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1906-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1906-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1906-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1906-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1906-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1906-world-series/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1906-world-series/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1906-world-series/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1906-world-series/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1906-world-series/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1906-world-series/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1906-world-series/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1906-world-series/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1878 Chicago White Stockings season** was the seventh season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third in the National League and the first at Lakefront Park.
[src:1906-world-series/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fourth in the National League with a record of 30–30.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The **1906 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1906 season.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The third edition of the World Series, it featured a crosstown matchup between the American League (AL) champion Chicago White Sox and the National League (NL) champion Chicago Cubs.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The Cubs had posted the highest regular-season win total (116) and winning percentage (.763) in the major leagues since the advent of the modern era in 1901.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The White Sox, known as the "Hitless Wonders" after finishing with the worst team batting average (.230) in the American League, beat the Cubs in six games for one of the greatest upsets in Series history as the Sox out-pitched the Cubs in their first two wins and out-hit them in their last two.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The White Sox won their first championship in franchise history, and this was the first major professional sports championship ever won by a Chicago-based team.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The home teams alternated, starting with the National League Cubs being home in Game 1.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The teams split the first four games; then the Hitless Wonders (a name coined by sportswriter Charles Dryden) exploded for 26 hits in the last two games.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] True to their nickname, the White Sox hit only .198 as a team in winning the series, but it beat the .196 average produced by the Cubs.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] In Game 3, White Sox pitcher Ed Walsh struck out 12 Cubs, breaking the previous record of 11 set by Bill Dinneen in 1903.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] National interest in the Series was strong.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Ahead of the third game, backers in Denver, Colorado offered a guarantee of US$10,000 (equivalent to $358,333 in 2025) to host the seventh game of the series should it be necessary.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The Spokane (Washington) Chamber of Commerce offered US$15,000 (equivalent to $537,500 in 2025) for the game.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The Series would remain in Chicago and finish in six games.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The 1906 World Series was the first to be played between two teams from the same metropolitan area or state.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] This series along with the 1944 edition (contested between the St.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Louis Browns), and the 1989 edition (contested between the San Francisco Giants and Oakland Athletics) are the only such instances outside of New York City where two teams from the same metropolitan area played in the World Series.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] This was also the last World Series where both teams were making their first appearance in the Fall Classic, something that is currently impossible without future expansion (as the Seattle Mariners are currently the only team in the league to have never appeared in a World Series).
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] White Sox starter Nick Altrock faced Cub starter Mordecai "Three-Fingered" Brown in game 1.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Both were perfect through three innings.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The Cubs put a runner on second in the bottom of the fourth inning, but couldn't score.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] In the top of the fifth, George Rohe tripled to lead off, then scored on an error at home when Patsy Dougherty reached on a fielder's choice.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The Sox scored a second run in the top of the sixth.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Altrock walked, and was sacrificed to second base by Ed Hahn.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Fielder Jones then singled to center but Altrock was thrown out at the plate, Jones taking second on the throw home.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] He took third on Cub catcher Johnny Kling's passed ball, and Frank Isbell drove him home with a single.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The Cubs struck back in their half of the sixth.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Kling walked and Brown singled with nobody out.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] After Solly Hofman sacrificed the runners to second and third, Altrock's wild pitch scored Kling and sent Brown to third, giving him little margin for error with only one out, but he got Jimmy Sheckard to pop out and Frank Schulte to ground out to end the threat.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] He pitched beautifully for the rest of the game, allowing only one more Cub to reach second, retaining the 2–1 lead for a Game 1 Sox win.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Ed Reulbach was called on for the Cubs to face White Sox hurler Doc White.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] After matching 1–2–3 first innings, things started to fall apart for White.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] After cleanup-hitting first baseman Frank Chance led off the top of the second with a strikeout, third baseman Harry Steinfeldt singled to left field and shortstop Joe Tinker beat out a bunt.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Cubs second baseman Johnny Evers then reached on a two-base error by White Sox second baseman Frank Isbell, scoring Steinfeldt for an unearned run and moving Tinker and Evers to second and third.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Catcher Johnny Kling was then intentionally walked to load the bases and bring up the pitcher, still with only one out.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Reulbach squeeze-bunted Tinker home for a second unearned run, moving Evers to third and Kling to second with two out.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Solly Hofman followed with an infield single to shortstop Lee Tannehill, scoring Evers for a third unearned run, but when Kling tried to score from second, he was thrown out at home plate, ending the rally.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The Cubs added a fourth unearned run in the third, ending Doc White's day on the mound.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The Sox scored in the bottom of the fifth inning with an unearned run, thanks to a wild pitch and an error.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The Cubs scored three more runs, all earned, in the sixth and eighth to win Game 2 7–1 and tie the Series at one game apiece.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Reulbach pitched the first one-hitter in World Series history.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] After allowing two first-inning hits, Sox starter "Big Ed" Walsh didn't give up another and struck out 12, giving the Sox a 2–1 edge in the series.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] After Fred Schulte's first inning two-out double, Walsh retired the next 25 of 27 Cub batters to face him.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Third baseman George Rohe cracked a two-out, bases-loaded triple to left in the top of the sixth off Jack Pfiester for the only runs of the game.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Looking to even the Series, the Cubs started Mordecai Brown on one day's rest who pitched 5+2⁄3 innings of no-hit ball for the Cubs before settling for a two-hitter.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Nick Altrock, who faced and defeated Brown in game 1, was the hard-luck loser, with the only run of the game coming on Johnny Evers' two-out single in the top of the seventh scoring Frank Chance.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The Sox put the tying run on second base in the top of the ninth thanks to a two-out walk and a passed ball, but Frank Isbell grounded out to end the threat.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The game took just 96 minutes and evened the Series at two games apiece.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Game 5 was a wild affair with a total of 18 hits, ten walks, six errors, two hit batsmen, three wild pitches and a steal of home.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The Cubs allowed a first inning run to the Sox, then scored three unearned runs on two Sox errors to take an early lead.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The Sox tied the game in the third on George Davis' theft of home on the front end of a double steal and then took the lead for good with a four-run rally in the fourth and held on for the victory to take a 3–2 lead in the series.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] A 12-hit attack led by Frank Isbell's four doubles were enough to overcome seven unearned runs by the Cubs caused by six errors committed by the normally solid Sox defense.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] "Big" Ed Walsh earned his second win of the series, although he needed three innings of relief help from Doc White.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Isbell would remain the sole major league player to get four extra-base hits in one postseason game until Shohei Ohtani hit two doubles and two home runs in Game 3 of the 2025 World Series.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Mordecai Brown, again pitching on only one day of rest, didn't make it out of the second inning as the Hitless Wonders White Sox stunned the 116–36 Cubs in the Series finale.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The Sox battered Brown for seven runs on eight hits while getting a solid pitching performance from Doc White.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] Although the Cubs scored a run and loaded the bases in the ninth, White got Frank Schulte to ground out for the final out of the series and the White Sox won the World Series.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] The powerful Cubs went on to win the next two World Series from the Detroit Tigers, despite falling far short of 116 wins in either season, for the last Cubs win in a World Series for over a hundred years.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] This game remains the only time the Chicago White Sox have clinched a postseason series in their home ballpark.
[src:1906-world-series/1906-world-series] It was the only time a Chicago-based team had ever clinched a series at home until the Cubs won the 2015 National League Division Series on their home field.
